    "Specifically, during pre-training, we further select one intermediate layer k as the supervised layer of GAN-based targets, besides the traditional HuBERT-based targets for the top layers, and calculate the masked prediction loss, which can besummarized as follows:L = - l∈{k,L} t∈M log p l (c l t |o l t)(2)where L is the number of encoder layer, M denotes the set of masked timesteps, c l t denotes the corresponding codes at timestep t, and o l t denotes the output hidden states of layer l at timestep t. The distribution over the codes is parameterized with:p l (c l t |o l t) = exp(sim(W l o l t, e l (c l t))/τ) c ′ ∈C exp(sim(W l o l t, e l (c ′))/τ)(3)TABLE I WER RESULTS ON LIBRISPEECH TEST SETS WHEN FINE-TUNED ON 1 HOUR, 10 HOURS, THE TRAIN-CLEAN-100, TRAIN-CLEAN-360, AND TRAIN-OTHER-500 SPLITS OF LIBRISPEECH.",
    "Model No LM LM clean other clean other 1-hour subset DeCoAR 2.0 [19] --13.8 29.1 DiscreteBERT [20] --9.0 17.6 wav2vec 2.0 [1] 24.5 29.7 5.5 11.3 HuBERT [2] 20.9 27.5 6.1 11.3 WavLM [3] 24.5 29.2 5.7 10.8 token2vec [12] 20.0 25.8 --T-HuBERT 16.4 22.2 6.4 11.9 10-hour subset DeCoAR 2.0 [19] --5.4 13.3 DiscreteBERT [20] --5.9 14.1 wav2vec 2.0 [1] 11.1 17.6 4.3 9.5 HuBERT [2] 10.1 16.8 4.3 9.4 WavLM [3] 9.8 16.0 4.3 9.2 token2vec [12] 9.0 14.9 --T-HuBERT 7.8 13.7 4.1 9.1 100-hour subset DeCoAR 2.0 [19] --5.0 12.1 DiscreteBERT [20] --4.5 12.1 wav2vec 2.0 [1] 6.1 13.3 3.4 8.0 HuBERT [2] 6.3 13.2 3.4 8.1 WavLM [3] 5.7 12.0 3.4 7.7 token2vec [12] 5.1 11.8 --PBERT [21] 4.2 9.5 3.1 7.2 SpeechLM-P [9] 3.4 8.1 2.7 6.2 T-HuBERT 4.8 10.0 3.1 7.0 360-hour subset HuBERT 4.8 11.0 3.0 7.2 T-HuBERT 3.8 9.1 2.7 6.4 500-hour subset HuBERT 4.8 10.1 3.0 6.7 T-HuBERT 3.7 8.1 2.6 5.9where W is the project matrix, and e is the embedding for code c. III.",
    "EXPERIMENTS A. DatasetsFor unsupervised speech pre-training, we use the publicly available 960-hour LibriSpeech [22] dataset.",
    "For unpaired text data, we use the LibriSpeech LM corpus 1, containing about 40M English sentences.",
    "For the downstream ASR task, we use the train-clean-100 split of LibriSpeech, the 1-hour and 10-hour split data of Libri-Light [23] as the low-resource scenarios."
